[00:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'One video is real, shot in my backyard, and this is the same video with alligators and a swamp added with Open Art VFX. &gt;&gt; If you have even the slightest visual creativity, you are going to love'

[00:12] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'today\'s video because we\'re going to talk about one of the most exciting AI tool sets to come along so far. That gal was able to transform her backyard into a swamp of alligators using Open Art\'s new VFX feature, which you will find in the video module. Now,'

[00:25] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'we\'re going to get into all sorts of ways to use this incredible tool today. Well, let me show you how simple it was just to create that video. &gt;&gt; [music] &gt;&gt; This will give you the basic foundation'

[00:37] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'of how this all works. First, she shoots video in her backyard. &gt;&gt; I have no idea how I get myself into these situations, but somehow I always get through it. &gt;&gt; We click here to upload that video,'

[00:52] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: '[music] or if we\'re using a video that we already have, we can just drag it right over here. You can select up to 10 seconds of the video to apply the effect to. Once you\'ve gotten that 10 seconds chosen, you click confirm. Now, you\'re going to select a mask, and this is where the magic happens. The most'

[01:04] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'important thing to know about a mask is that it protects an area from being changed. So, if you want to change the background, you want to mask the subject. If you want to change the subject, you want to mask the background. In this case, all we had to do was make sure the VFX tab was'

[01:17] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'selected. We drag or upload the video that we want to change. We apply a mask, then we provide it with a reference photo to tell VFX how to change the image. [music] So, we just drag that reference image here, and because we mask everything but the yard, when we'

[01:29] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'generate this video, the grass is replaced by alligators. &gt;&gt; I have no idea how I get myself into these situations, but somehow I always get through it. &gt;&gt; So, as you can probably tell, masking is'

[01:43] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'a very important part of this process. [music] And now, I\'m going to show you several different ways you can use masking to get a variety of effects using the VFX module. So, let me show you a final result, and then we\'ll talk about how to get there. Now, in this'

[01:55] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'original video, the man is carrying a cardboard box around his living room, and he has some kids walking around. So, let\'s [music] talk about how we can change various elements in this video, and we\'ll start with the background. Just like before, we\'re going to drag our source video into this area here,'

[02:07] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'confirm the clip we want to edit, and now we select a mask. So, let\'s dig into these [music] mask selection tools a little bit. The very first one here is the auto select. It\'s going [music] to detect the main subject, in this case the man holding the cardboard box,'

[02:19] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'automatically. Now, remember when the man is selected, he\'s protected. So, if we want only change the background, we would leave things just like this. But, let\'s go through the rest of these selection tools. The smart select tool analyzes the picture and identifies various objects, so you can click them'

[02:32] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'one at a time. So, if we just wanted to select the cardboard box, we can just click it, and it will select that cardboard box. If you\'re going to add additional areas, it\'s a good practice [music] to click on add an area and to make something separate, so that each'

[02:44] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'area has its own mask. So, if I wanted to select the man, I click him, and if there\'s an area here that needs to be added, I would just click that, and it would add it to the mask. [music] Here, you can see it\'s a little messy, that\'s when you would use something like the brush tool, which you can adjust the'

[02:56] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'size here from teeny tiny all the way to large, [music] and then you would just brush those areas in and clean that up just like this to make sure the areas you wanted were selected. The erase tool allows you to erase anything that is on that particular area that you have'

[03:08] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'chosen. So, for example, right now, because the box is a separate area, I cannot erase it until I choose area one, and then I can erase it. This allows you to undo and redo, and the trash can clears everything. Now, another way to select areas is just to identify [music]'

[03:21] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'them with text. So, if I click on add an area again and describe areas to include, if I wanted the cardboard box selected, I would just type cardboard box, and it\'s selected. Well, let\'s say I wanted to add the ceiling, I could just click add area, type ceiling, and'

[03:33] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'it\'s [music] selected. If this is the area you want to change, and everything else you want to stay the'

[03:45] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'same, then we need to protect this area, and it\'s a lot simpler just to to the subject instead of all of these various pieces, [music] and then click the invert mask tool. You\'ll probably find yourself using this a lot as you go along. If you need to adjust the'

[03:57] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'transparency of the mask, you can use this slider here, and of course, we can zoom in and out of the picture as we choose. So, we\'ve got the subject selected. I\'m going to use the paintbrush here just to clean that up, make sure we\'ve got all that. And now we want to change the background. So, we\'re'

[04:09] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'going to click on preview here. We just make sure that we\'ve got selected what we want. This little area right here is a little messy. Let\'s go back [music] and fix that. We\'re just going to click the small brush and the erase tool and just kind of get in there. Most of the time stuff like that doesn\'t really'

[04:21] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'matter. The model\'s smart enough to compensate for that, but just to be sure. So, now we\'ll click preview again. We see that we\'ve got everything we want. It\'s okay if it\'s a little bit messy. It truly is. Click on confirm. Now we get to define what the background looks like, and you do that here in the'

[04:33] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'target look of the output. If you have an image you want to use as a background, you can upload that here, or you can refer to your history and use anything you\'ve ever generated in the past. 99% of the time I\'m using create with AI, because when you click on that,'

[04:46] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'it pulls in the video and finds the first frame. And here\'s where you prompt exactly what you want the changes to be. Now, if you\'ve done any kind of image editing with models that allow you to just text your way to a change, the same thing is happening here. This little at'

[04:59] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'frame zero is referring to the frame that we are on, and we can scroll through and choose which image we want to use as the starting point for our change. I\'m going to go back to the beginning, in this case frame one, and I\'m going to type a prompt. And just'

[05:12] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'like everything else in the OpenArt platform, if we want to refer to a reference image, we\'re going to type the at symbol, and we\'re going to see any available choices. Right now, we just have that one. Something to keep in mind when we type this prompt is we want the composition of this image we\'re about to create to stay as close to this original'

[05:25] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'as possible. In other words, we don\'t want the man on the other side of the room. We don\'t want the composition of the room changed. So, if we make the prompt leaving the composition of the room, and then we reference that first [music] frame and the position of the man exactly the same, he\'s in an alien'

[05:38] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'spacecraft. And then in a few seconds, it\'s going to generate an [music] image. So, now we have this image, and the man and the box have stayed the same. Now, in the prompt, you can give it specific instructions. Since this is a simple background replacement, I really don\'t even need to [music] type a prompt'

[05:51] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'unless I want to. So, I might say something like, "The man is walking cautiously through the [music] corridors of an alien spaceship." and then generate that. Now, while this is working, you might be wondering why we wouldn\'t use the replace background [music] here instead of the VFX. Well, you absolutely could. If you simply want'

[06:04] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'to change the background and you don\'t need to change any of the other elements, a simple background replacement is generally a good idea. You don\'t need to mask anything. The model\'s very intelligent and it does a great job. But, if we want to change more details about the subject itself or things that are going on in the room or'

[06:18] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'how the subject is interacting with the environment, this is when you would use the VFX feature. So, now here\'s the video we get. &gt;&gt; Okay, everybody stay close, &gt;&gt; [music] &gt;&gt; but but not too close, okay? Be alert. &gt;&gt; Now, you\'ll notice that the camera'

[06:30] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'movement also moves along with the man, so it works [music] in the space. So, that\'s a simple background replacement, but what if we want to do something more complicated like not only replace the background, but also change out that cardboard box for a weapon. Process is'

[06:42] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the same. We bring in our video and then when we select our mask, you\'ll see that only this part of the man is protected, which [music] means that the background and the gun and even the position of his hands is all up for changing. You end up with something that looks like this,'

[06:55] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'which could totally be cleaned [music] up, but it didn\'t even really matter. This reference image was created the exact same way as before. We clicked on create with AI. We type a prompt similar to leaving the composition of the room and then we refer to that first frame and the position of the man exactly the'

[07:08] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'same. He\'s walking through an alien spacecraft holding an alien weapon. Then [music] when we generate that, that\'s when we get this image. &gt;&gt; Okay, everybody stay close, but but not too close, okay? Be alert. &gt;&gt; And if you wanted to change his'

[07:21] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'clothing, I\'ll bet you see what\'s coming. When we select our mask, the only thing we\'re protecting is his head. And again, really sloppy mask on my part here. And this time we prompted not only the background and the weapon, but also tactical gear that he\'s wearing. That\'s'

[07:33] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'what gives us this image and this resulting video. &gt;&gt; Okay, everybody stay close, but but not too close, okay? &gt;&gt; Now, a couple quick tips before we move on. If you do not like the reference image that was generated, you\'re not stuck with it. Just like any other image'

[07:45] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'in Open Art, we can just find it here in our gallery and we can either click on recreate image and try to re-prompt it, or we can bring it in as a reference image and just do any type of text edit we want. Like for example, give it a blue and purple theme [music] instead of'

[07:58] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'pink and green. Once that\'s generated, you can just drag it in here and replace that one and then when you render it, you\'ll have that background. But also, when you create the video, don\'t be afraid to try to add elements in through prompting. For example, here I said, "Dad is walking through the halls of a spaceship in full head-to-toe tactical'

[08:10] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'gear as his tiny robot minions gather around him." But notice, I actually had him masked here so that his clothing was protected, so we\'re not going to get the tactical gear. But we do get some tiny robot minions at the end. &gt;&gt; Okay, everybody stay close, but but not'

[08:22] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'too [music] close, okay? Be alert. &gt;&gt; Here\'s a couple of examples where we take him out of the alien spacecraft and into the planet Earth in various'

[08:35] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'situations. So you can see we have all kinds of creative flexibility here. Now, any filmmaker knows that the environment of your video is not just some random choice. It has a very specific purpose and in many cases, the environment sets the emotional tone of the scene you\'re'

[08:47] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'looking at. Change the environment, change the tone. Let\'s look at some examples. Here we have this [music] base video of a woman with a kind of sullen expression just wandering around her apartment. If we drag that video into VFX and apply a mask where she is'

[08:59] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'selected and protected, and then using [music] the techniques we looked at before, put her in a snowy scene. Although she is still sullen, the emotional tone has changed somewhat simply because of her environment. If [music] your character\'s feeling depressed, you might have her walk'

[09:11] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'around in the fog. If she\'s got a lot on her mind and she\'s walking around outside contemplating thoughts that are flying in from everywhere, we might put her in a windy environment. Now, for the most part, you could probably get away with using background replacements for this, but in this case, I wanted to'

[09:23] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'change her outfit. So I [music] did create a mask that protected just her head and hair and everything else can change, the environment and her clothing. Now, sometimes in filmmaking, you\'re going to need your character or your subject to be in an an precarious situation that would be'

[09:35] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'completely impractical to do in real life unless you\'re Tom Cruise. So here we just have a few seconds of a man walking through [music] an office building completely safe and free from potential harm, but we want to change'

[09:47] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'that. So let\'s select a mask. This will be an easy one. We\'re just going to auto select the subject because we want everything around him to change. We\'ll just confirm that preview. So again, we\'ll create a reference image with AI. Here we\'ve given it a prompt saying'

[09:59] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'leave everything the same except and then I\'ve got a fairly detailed prompt that describes the background of the cliffs and the clouds in the sky and exactly his environment. [music] end up with this starting image. You\'ll see that the prompt here is a lot more detailed visual style environment'

[10:12] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'camera. It\'s all laid out there. That\'s because I used an LLM to help me write a more detailed prompt to see what kind of impact it would have if I was more detailed. Here\'s what we got. But now let\'s make it even more'

[10:29] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'precarious by just changing the reference image and the prompt. So the video\'s the same, the mask is the same, but now we have him walking along steel girders on a skyscraper. I know I\'m never doing that in real'

[10:42] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'life. Here\'s another version of base footage of Cindy playing on the monkey bars here. If we protect her with a mask and then provide a reference image that looks like [music] this, we create a very dangerous situation. Now let\'s take a look at a few more'

[10:58] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'examples that combine these techniques in various ways to give you an idea of the range of things that\'s possible and believe me, my imagination is probably way more limited than yours. &gt;&gt; [music]'

[11:10] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: '&gt;&gt; So now that you know how easy it is to'

[11:27] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'transform your video footage with these incredible VFX tools, it\'s time for you to get in there and start experimenting. [music] The fastest way to do that is get yourself an Open Art subscription if you don\'t have one already and utilize [music] what we taught you here in this video. Because we\'ve reached the time in'

[11:40] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'this creative evolution where the question is no longer, I wonder if I can do this. The question is, what will you create? Now, to learn even more about what\'s possible with VFX, be sure to catch Erman\'s last video. It was an incredible overview of what this tool'

